md:LocalizedInfo.md:Summary190: Prepare for a new era of magic with Fantastic Beasts. Starring Eddie Redmayne, explore the adventures of writer Newt Scamander in New York's secret community of witches and wizards seventy years before Harry Potter reads his book in school.

md:LocalizedInfo.md:TitleDisplayUnlimited: Before Harry Potter: A New Era of Magic Begins!
md:LocalizedInfo.md:TitleSort: Before Harry Potter: A New Era of Magic Begins!
md:LocalizedInfo.md:Summary190: Join J.K. Rowling as she, David Yates, and David Heyman return to Leavesden studios to build a new and exciting corner of the Wizarding Universe.
A wizard who is more comfortable with beasts than he is with other human beings. Explore Newt's character, costume and journey in the film.
Magical sisters with a strong bond. Cast and crew discuss Tina and Queenie's characters, costumes, and journeys in the film.
A No-Maj who is magical in his own way. Cast and crew discuss Jacob's character, costume, and journey in the film.
A family intolerant of magic. Cast and crew discuss the family's characters, costumes, and journeys in the film.
Two of MACUSA's finest. Cast and crew discuss their characters, costumes, and journeys in the film.
Venture into the magical world of beasts and the creative team behind them.
Meet Picket: A Bowtruckle with attachment issues. Discover the Bowtruckle's character, what a Bowtruckle is and how it was created for the film.
Meet the beast with the power of invisibility. Uncover the Demiguise's character, what a Demiguise is and how it was created for the film.
Meet the beast that dances with Newt. Cast and crew discuss the Erumpent's character, what an Erumpent is, and how it was created for the film.
Meet the beast that loves anything shiny. Cast and crew discuss the Niffler's character, what a Niffler is, and how it was created for the film.
Meet the beast with the ability to change its size. Learn about the Occamy's character, what an Occamy is and how it was created for the film.
Meet the bird that can change the weather. Explore the Thunderbird's character, what a Thunderbird is and how it was created for the film.

md:LocalizedInfo.md:Summary190: Meet the team behind the construction, design, costumes & props of the Wizarding World and discover how the massive sets were created.
Explore the streets of New York City in 1926. An inside look at the construction, detail and design that went into creating New York.
Explore the halls of MACUSA. An inside look at the construction, detail and design that went into creating MACUSA.
Explore Newt's magical case. An inside look at the construction, detail and design that went into creating Newt's magical case.
Explore the Shaw Banquet. An inside look at the construction, detail and design that went into creating Shaw's Banquet.
Explore the Blind Pig. An inside look at the construction, detail and design that went into creating the Blind Pig.

manifest:TextObject.manifest:TextString: J.K. Rowling originally wrote "Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them" as a small side project for charity.
It began as a textbook on magical creatures for Harry Potter to use in school
She fell in love with the character of Newt Scamander and decided to give him a backstory.
Newt is played by Eddie Redmayne in this film.
Redmayne's favorite "Harry Potter" film is "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 2."
Redmayne's favorite "Harry Potter" book is "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," or, as it's known internationally, "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
Between the mid-1800s and the 1920s, passenger ships were the primary means of immigration to the U.S.
By the 1920s, passage between England and the United States by ship would take around 5 days.
600 background actors were used in this scene.
Q: Why did Newt go in through No-Maj customs?
A: He was transporting magical creatures at a time when this was illegal. No-Majs were far easier to fool than the wizarding checkpoint would have been.
A number of versions of Newt's case were used in the film.
Some of them were made to be especially lightweight for long walking or standing scenes.
This NYC set was built in England. Almost every aspect of the city was designed and built from scratch for this film.
When asked why Colin Farrell was chosen for this role, Rowling responded, "That quiet menace. He's amazing... He can brood."
Colin was born in Dublin, Ireland.
His father and his uncle played professional soccer for the Shamrock Rovers.
Costume designer Colleen Atwood personally approved every single outfit for each extra.
All of the New York street sets were built in a T-shape divided into three parts: a street with a luxurious bank, an impoverished tenement neighborhood and a middle-class brownstone.
Katherine Waterston was first invited to audition for the role of Tina via email.
She didn't think she had any chance of getting the part.
When Dan Fogler found out that he had been cast as Jacob, he was at Comic-Con promoting his graphic novel "Brooklyn Gladiator."
He was so excited that he started giving away free copies to Comic-Con 2015 attendees.
Beginning in 1692, townspeople in colonial Massachusetts began a frenzied search for witches.
Of more than 150 innocent people accused of witchcraft, at least twelve women and six men were put to death.
In the real-life 1920s, the fear of Communism caused public panic and mass hysteria, while fears over witchcraft were obsolete.
Redmayne said the most challenging part of his role was learning to "interact with [the beasts] with a kind of fluency that made you really believe in his love of them..."
This set is modeled after the famous Tweed Courthouse in New York.
This is an Occamy egg.
Occamies are widely hunted within magical circles because they lay eggs of pure silver.
World War I spanned from 1914 to 1918.
"Expeditionary force" describes any squad of troops sent to serve or fight in a foreign country.
Costume designer Colleen Atwood created Newt's costume first.
She made his outfit a bit mismatched because she wanted to convey "quirkiness."
She also used mostly warm-colored fabric because of the popularity of similar tones during that era.
Redmayne chose his characters wand very carefully.
The art department gave him 12 wands to choose from.
Redmayne chose the wand he felt would resonate the most with Newt.
According to J.K. Rowling, Newt is the first Magizoologist since the introduction of the Statute of Secrecy 300 years ago.
In the 1920s, buying goods and services on credit became exponentially more popular.
For the first time, using credit became the norm for people without immediate cash.
During the 20s, 60% of families bought their cars on credit.
To create many of this film's visual effects, 3D digital scans were taken of each cast member and used to animate photo-realistic movement sequences.
The props department built a special foam version of Newt's case so that Redmayne wouldn't get injured in this scene.
Waterston said of comparisons to Hermione, "There are people who have really high expectations for what we're doing."
"...I have to not think about that so that I can be free and play...every day"
The MACUSA is the Magical Congress of the United States of America.
In the "Harry Potter" series, Fred and George Weasley breed miniature puffskeins called Pygmy Puffs. Ginny Weasley kept one as a pet.
Every decorative art piece in this scene was created by the film's special sculpture department.
The sculptors designed most of the sculptures using computer graphics, then used a sculpting technology similar to a robotic arm to cut figures from stone and metal.
The sculptors then detailed these figure by hand before sending them to the painting department for material finishes.
The figures were then placed on bases and given to the scenic painter, who applied final touches.
The sculptors made 14 human figure sculptures, mostly of important magical figures, for the MACUSA building.
Katherine Waterston is an acclaimed stage actress as well as a screen actress.
She played Anya in a celebrated stage revival of "The Cherry Orchard."
The interior of the MACUSA was inspired by the Siena Cathedral in Siena, Italy.
This monument to the Salem witch trials was actually built. It's not CGI.
Grindelwald was the first dark wizard to threaten world order.
In 1945, he was famously involved in a three-way duel with Albus Dumbledore and his brother Aberforth, which resulted in the tragic death of the Dumbledore's sister Ariana.
In 1888, Cynthia Leonard became the first woman to run for mayor of New York City.
To this day, New York City has never had a female mayor.
Seraphina wears stacked rings on her left hand because actress Carmen Ejogo is left-handed and wanted to highlight that.
Newt has been across every continent except North America, where his plans for studying indigenous magical wildlife are postponed by the series of events in this film.
Production designer Stuart Craig filled this basement set with actual logbooks written in intricate 1920s-era handwriting.
The logbooks are even filled with completed wizard certificates!
Ezra Miller says, "Getting the role [of Credence] was a moment of absolute ecstatic joy and sort of transcendent sense of completion."
"I was doing some sort of dance in the streets of New York City, dropping to my knees, crying, praising the heavens."
"People [were] looking at me like I should be institutionalized."
For this film, the wardrobe department was responsible for dressing an average of 200 actors per day.
Indoor plumbing and electric lighting did not become new standards in urban tenements such as this until the early 1920s.
Newt's case contains approximately 80 creatures.
Fogler is a New York native.
For the New Yorkers in the cast, it was strange going all the way to the UK to film on a set replicating 1920s New York.
On the theme of this film, Rowling says, "For me, there is nothing more interesting than human nature."
"So although the title is 'Fantastic Beasts,' to me, we're talking about the beast that's in everyone and the way that we make beasts of others."
"Right now people are very attracted to the idea of drawing lines... It is such a dangerous thing to...say, 'You're wrong, you're insufficient and you should be treated thus.'"
"That's at the heart of most of what I write, and it's certainly at the heart of this movie."
Of the film's protagonists, Rowling says, "My heroes are always people who will say, I see how it is, but it doesn't have to be that way,' who will ask, 'Well, why is it this way?'"
To create era-appropriate sets such as this, production referred to 1920s postcards for visual inspiration.
Ezra Miller sang in the Metropolitan Opera Children's Chorus.
Jon Voight, who plays Henry Shaw Sr., is a fan of the last three "Harry Potter" movies in particular, all directed by David Yates.
Between takes of this scene, Voight picked up an inkwell on his desk, thinking it was empty.
As it turns out, the set decorators had filled it with ink, and the ink stained his hands for the rest of the shoot day.
Jenn Murray, who plays Chastity Barebone, read all of the "Harry Potter" books and saw the films.
She described them as "sort of like escapism, and so beautifully written."
Jon Voight and his two on-screen sons (played by Ronan Raftery and Josh Cowdery) became friends and hung out off set.
They even went to the movies together.
This NYC set was built in England.
The interiors and exteriors of most buildings were created from scratch for this film.
Alison Sudol, who plays Queenie, is a self-described "Potterhead" who read each of the "Harry Potter" books and watched all of the films as a young girl.
According to Rowling, one of the reasons Alison was right for the role of Queenie because she has an "otherworldly quality."
When she read the script, Alison fell in love her character's ability to empathize with and show kindness toward others.
Sudol learned and perfected a new accent for her role in "Fantastic Beasts" early in filming because she "couldn't find her unless [she] spoke like [her.]"
Waterston has a real-life sister, with whom she has described her bond as "a little bit mysterious and really deep."
She says that they have had shared dreams and even shown up to lunch accidentally wearing the same outfit.
All the magazine covers in Tina and Queenie's house display original art inspired by hand drawings from the 1920s.
Miller, a native of NYC, was impressed with the accuracy of the Manhattan sets.
The sets even included fake smog and fake industrial fumes.
Miller describes them as, "These horrible smoke...and steam fumes that we New Yorkers never question"
This film takes place in 1926.
When asked what excited her most about the Fantastic Beasts script, Katherine Waterston said, I just loved Tina and felt a connection to her.
The Props Department designed a special version of Newts case that the actors could climb into. The set was raised and made with a hole so the actors could walk down into it.
The inside of Newt's case was originally modeled by the art department to resemble a Garden of Eden for all creatures.
However, J.K. Rowling felt strongly that Newt did not have the extraordinary powers of a wizard like Dumbledore or Voldemort, and, therefore the design should be more handmade.
These creatures, called Grindylows, were featured in "Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire."
This scene is comprised of a number of discrete shots that have been combined using visual effects.
Rowling calls Newt's case "a portable animal hospital/safari park for endangered species."
The creatures in this film were created using a mixture of animation, image capture, and cinematography.
Rowling created the Thunderbird to represent North American mythology. The creature is reminiscent of Dumbledore's Phoenix, Fawkes. In terms of symbology, Rowling says, "I love birds."
Different parts of Newt's case evolve to resemble each beast's natural habitat.
Jacob Kowalskis similarly lovable and loyal counterpart in theHarry Potterseries would be Ron Weasley.
Rowling said, "Jacob softens Newt to an extent. That friendship is very touching, and I've loved writing that."
A group of Bowtruckles is called a "branch."
This Occamy nest is made of bent bamboo.
Newts case contains an artificial sun and moon, which he controls to help animals maintain their natural sleep patterns.
Redmayne studied animal trainers to prepare for his role as Newt.
He joined zookeepers and safari park attendants to learn about their interactions with animals.
He was especially touched by animal care professionals who slept alongside newborn cubs to mimic motherhood.
Redmayne felt this represented the incredible bonds that can form between animals and humans.
These creatures are called Mooncalves.
The Mooncalves' environment was designed to look like a planet that has been taken apart and put back together imperfectly.
The movement of the obscurus was inspired by the dark, chaotic brushstrokes of Francis Bacon paintings.
To prepare for this film, Redmayne stayed with a completely off-the-grid wilderness man for several days to study his skills and affectations.
Redmayne's gait in this film is modeled after an animal tracking method this man taught him.
Rowling says, "Ezra is extraordinary...as an actor...and he's also a very unusual person. Credence requires a certain genius to represent accurately. Ezra's phenomenal in the part."
Collin Farrell calls director David Yates "an extraordinary man and filmmaker who feels like a protector of the kingdom."
Farrell speaks German and French.
He once auditioned for the Irish boy band Boyzone.
Due to a rush of mass migration to major cities, factory workers in NYC suffered from job insecurity and had to make do with harsh working conditions.
Eddie Redmayne's great-grandfather was Sir Richard Redmayne, a celebrated English engineer who greatly improved British mine safety.
"Fantastic Beasts" had a special picture vehicle coordinator, Alex King. His department's job was to read the script and decipher which cars would be needed in each scene.
His crew bought, restored and positioned each car.
The mass production of cars following Henry Ford's introduction of The Model T granted new freedom and mobility to Americas youth culture.
By 1927, Ford had sold 15 million assembly-line vehicles, revolutionizing the American way of life.
Rowling says, "If you don't love the Niffler, there's something wrong with you."
The special effects team made many of the items in this scene with breakaway glass, which shatters easily and dramatically.
The bikes on which some of the police officers ride were authentic 1920s Indian Scout motorcycles, which the vehicle department sourced from Europe and then painted to look fresh.
Fogler won a Tony Award in 2005 for his performance in a musical play called "The 25th Annual Putnam County Spelling Bee."
He is also a graphic novelist.
For this scene, cinematographer Philippe Rousselot worked with the lighting department to build huge, moving LED lights to simulate shadows cast by clouds in front of the moon.
The Central Park Zoo that exists today was not built until 1934. Opened in 1864, the "zoo" was more like a small menagerie of exotic animals.
The special effects department designed a real brick archway, which they collapsed using hydraulic rams. Later, visual effects placed the actors and environment back into the scene digitally.
An Erumpent horn appeared in "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 1."
To orchestrate the arch collapse, the special effects department ran extensive tests to see how the arch would react to varying amounts of pressure.
Redmayne's peacock-blue coat was equipped with hidden pockets.
Costume designer Colleen Atwood included them based on her research into magicians' coats.
The Graphics team actually wrote and printed this 1920s-era political pamphlet, including campaign pitches and promises to lower taxes.
This scene was shot in St. George's Hall, an iconic neo-Grecian building in Liverpool, England.
St. George's Hall was the site the site of a massive 25,000-person gathering following John Lennon's death in 1980.
The poster behind Senator Shaw is 35 feet tall and was painted by hand.
Movie portrait painter Barnaby Gorton created two versions of this poster, each by hand, to have available in case of reshoots.
Each poster took three days to paint.
The costume department dressed each magical representative according to their country of origin.
The countries represented include Thailand, Hungary, Mongolia, Russia and Pakistan.
Newt's older brother is a noted Auror, which is a magical person who finds and catches Dark wizards.
Ezra Miller played Patrick in popular teen film "The Perks of Being a Wallflower." His favorite part of filming was dressing up as Dr. Frank-N-Furter from "The Rocky Horror Picture Show."
J.K. Rowling says her favorite subjects are outsiders who have been stigmatized, whom she calls "beasted characters."
She is fascinated by the close bonds that form between people who seem different.
According to Rowling, the Barebone family descends from a wizard.
Rowling's favorite character of the entire Potter series is Albus Dumbledore.
In 1921, Dumbledore was a young professor at Hogwarts.
One of Farrell's favorite books is "When Nietzsche Wept" by Irvin D. Yalom.
He supports a number of charitable causes, such as Stand Up! and Homeless World Cup.
J.K. Rowling first jotted down her ideas for "Harry Potter" on a napkin, and then wrote the novel using an old typewriter.
Rowling was turned down by 12 publishers before a small publishing house, Bloomsbury, gave her a chance.
Sudol is a singer, songwriter, and pianist. She has released four albums under the stage name A Fine Frenzy.
She has shared the stage with artists like Rufus Wainright and The Stooges.
When working with on set, actors were provided with eye lines.
These showed the actors exactly where to look to interact realistically with elements inserted using visual effects.
Rowling says, "Queenie is underestimated constantly."
"She's very beautiful and people look at her, but they don't realize how much she can see in [those] who are really objectifying her."
"So...the girl who's always looked at can see more deeply than anyone else."
When Fogler was in high school, he played the baker in "Into the Woods."
"Fantastic Beasts" was the longest project Dan Fogler has worked on, as it shot for about six months.
Special effects designers created three special rigs that moved Katherine around the room as though she were being magically transported.
Each rig was equipped with a chair with an independent motor for spinning.
When asked what she thought of David Yate's choice of Eddie Redmayne for the part of Newt, Rowling responded, "He's perfect."
In 2014, Redmayne won an Academy Award for his portrayal of famed paralyzed physicist Stephen Hawking in the film "The Theory of Everything." (A.M.P.A.S.)
Hawking said of Redmayne's performance that at times he truly felt he was watching himself.
Redmayne was the first person born in the 1980s to win an Oscar.
In 2015, Redmayne was nominated for another Best Actor award for his portrayal of a trans woman in "The Danish Girl."
Miller is a huge "Harry Potter" fan. As a child, he read all of the books and would listen to the audio versions before bed.
According to Farrell, the costume department fit his shoes with small lifts, which made him a little taller.
The "it" girls of the 1920s were called flappers.
Their styles of dress and behavior were characterized by nonconformity and modernity.
They challenged traditional ideas of femininity by wearing makeup, speaking frankly and smoking tobacco in public.
During Prohibition Era in the 1920s, New York City was home to between 20,000 and 100,000 speakeasies.
Speakeasies were bars where residents drank and entertained illegally. They were often underground or in hidden rooms, and required secret passwords to gain entry.
This creature is an goblin. To create it, the visual effects department captured the movements of actors dancing around in reflective suits. This process is called motion capture.
The popularization of Jazz resulted from the Harlem Renaissance - a creative movement sparked by the mass migration of African Americans to northern cities following World War One.
In 1927, Warner Bros. released "The Jazz Singer," the first feature-length film to use audio dialogue as a part of dramatic action. The film was shot in New York City.
This character is a goblin named Gnarlak.
"Harry Potter" fans saw their first goblin in the lobby of Gringotts Bank in "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
Gnarlak is voiced by actor Ron Perlman. In this scene, he delivered his lines offstage while a double sat in his chair so that actors would have the correct eyeline.
The visual effects department then created a scaled section of the set and filmed Perlman separately using digital scanning technology.
This footage was used as a base for the motions and mannerisms of the digitally produced Gnarlak. He was then composited into the live action.
Hagrid, who was the foremost magical creature caretaker in the "Harry Potter" series, mentioned a Bowtruckle in the movie "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 1."
He described infant Harry Potter, when he brought him to live with the Dursleys, as "no bigger than a Bowtruckle."
Misunderstood heroes are a recurring theme in Rowling's work. Do these wanted posters remind you of anything?
The surging popularity of jazz led to the establishment of new popular dances in the Roaring Twenties.
Some of these dances were the Charleston, the Shimmy, the Turkey Trot, the Cake Walk and the Bunny Hop.
The most popular nightclub in Harlem during this period was the Cotton Club.
The Cotton Club was home to seminal musicians such as Louis Armstrong and Duke Ellington.
Because he went to an all-boys high school, Eddie Redmayne played female roles on the stage.
This creature is called a Demiguise.
It is Rowling's favorite beast.
As a kid, Fogler played Dungeons & Dragons.
Tina's costume was designed to include trousers, which was uncommon in traditional female attire of the '20s.
This felt appropriate for her character, who was written as exceptionally modern and driven for a woman of her time.
The graphics department had to add makeshift green screens to Tina's wanted poster so that the image could move in a 3D fashion.
According to director David Yates, one of the main character arcs in "Fantastic Beasts" is Newt's development of relationship skills.
He becomes friends with other humans, as opposed to only animals.
This attic was decorated with hundreds of actual objects common in the 1920s.
Many creature special effects, such as those in this scene, were created using motion-capture technology.
This is a very complex process that involves infrared cameras and computerized equations.
Motion capture helps animators to mimic realistic motion effectively.
3D scans of many props were taken for the visual effects department.
"Fantastic Beasts" is the acting debut for Faith Wood-Blagrove, who plays Modesty.
J.K. Rowling's full name is Joanne Rowling.
The first fan letter Rowling ever got was from a girl named Francesca. It began, "Dear sir"
The first print run of "Harry Potter" was only one thousand copies. At the time, Rowling was a single mother living in poverty.
Waterston is a big fan of the "Harry Potter" books, which she read as an adult.
Katherine Waterston believes that J.K. Rowling's storytelling is successful because it does not condescend. It is therefore accessible to children and adults alike.
"Harry Potter" fans were first introduced to the Lestrange family through the villain Bellatrix Lestrange.
